{
  "text": "The second account is the \"cortical binding of relational activity\" (CoBRA) theory [CITATION_1] , which suggests that, during retrieval, the vPPC (including the AnG) acts as a convergence zone that becomes increasingly involved after initial encoding to bind together episodic features that are represented in disparate neocortical regions. This account builds on anatomical features of the vPPC-its central location and connections to many neocortical regions [CITATION_2] )-which make it well situated for binding episodic memories by establishing intermodal links across diverse event features. CoBRA critically predicts that tasks that demand the reinstatement of intermodal features such as voices with faces will depend more on the vPPC than tasks that depend on within-modality associations. This account has received support from several studies [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , but other examinations of CoBRA were inconclusive, with multimodal integration deficits found in parietal lesion patients [CITATION_5] but no multimodal versus unimodal associative memory effects on parietal scalp ERPs recorded in healthy volunteers [CITATION_6] .",
  "correct_citation": {
